Within hours of the schoolyard shootings

that left five children and the gunman dead and 30 wounded Tuesday, dozens of translators rushed to assist the many Southeast Asian parents who arrived at the hospital desperate for word of their youngsters.
Many of the parents speak no English and were unable to ask whether their children were among those killed or wounded when a heavily armed gunman in combat fatigues invaded Cleveland Elementary School and opened fire before taking his own life.
"They do have people on staff at the hospital, but they are so overloaded they need every extra person they can secure," said Dixon, whose organization began calling throughout Stockton for volunteers speaking Southeast Asian languages.
